We recommended that Management: 

a.Immediately discontinue the practice of splitting purchase orders to circumvent the law on procurement;

b. Strictly adhere to the laws, rules and regulations in the procurement of goods and services such that competitive public bidding be adopted in all its procurement activities and resort to alternative methods of procurement only if the condition set forth under Section 48 to 53 of R.A.  No. 9184 are met, to promote economy and efficiency in operations; 

c.	Should the LGU decide to adopt an alternative mode of procurement, ensure that necessary posting requirements are met; and 

d.	Ensure all pertinent supporting documents are properly and consistently accomplished, and free from any form of erasures/alterations in order to preserve the integrity of the documents.

We recommended to the Mayor through the Accounting Unit: 

a.To strengthen internal control in the granting of Cash Advances to avoid unliquidated Cash advances at year end which shall include but not limited to establishing cash advance cut-offs on December, monitoring those with previously unsettled balances and prohibiting them from drawing new cash advances unless prior CAs are already settled;

b.To prohibit cash advance settlements on staggard basis, immediate liquidation should be applied whereof; 

c. To enforce immediate settlement of unliquidated cash advances;

d. To stop from drawing Municipality funds to cover for employee’s undeducted loan remittances and;

e. Demand immediate settlement of the Due from Officers and Employees Account.

Recommendations:

We recommended to Management to:

For Financial Assistance ₱2,505,000, submit proof of posting as required in the Joint Memorandum Circular as well as the supporting documents to warrant eligibility of grantees and amount granted;

For the Bidding ₱600,000 submit official receipts from Engr. Rey Almerol and Engr. Rey Bogahod;

For Patronal Town Fiesta ₱341,400 submit official receipts from Barangays in acknowledgment of assistances received;

For Aid to ABC ₱186,000 submit legal basis.

For Aid to BAC ₱85,700 submit legal basis.

Recommendations:

We recommended to the Management to:

a. Require the contractor, Mr. Joenard M. Tudtud to provide official receipts for the subject transactions;

b. Provide dates of actual usage of the rented equipment duly certified under oath by responsible LGU employee to support the amount already paid by the LGU;

c. For succeeding similar transactions of the LGU, prepare an Agency Evaluation of Equipment Utilization or any similar document indicating the estimated number of days when the equipment will be used and regularly require details on the dates of actual usage of rented equipment duly confirmed by responsible LGU employee as basis of the amount to be paid to contractors, for counter-checking.

We recommended and management agreed to:
Instruct the property officer to prepare and properly accomplish the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for the unserviceable properties;
Create a disposal committee to accelerate the evaluation and determination of the appraised value of the unserviceable properties listed in the IIRUP and cause them to prepare the appraisal report and disposal schedule;
Refer to COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1 dated January 30, 2024 otherwise known as the Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties for guidance;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to secure a copy of the Certificate of Ownership of the motorized fishing boats to be used as supporting documents for the dropping of these properties from agency books; and
Direct the Municipal Agriculture Office to keep copies of original Memorandum of Agreement in a secured location and/or secure a scanned copy of these documents as back-up files.

We recommended that Management:  

a. 	Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere with the prescribed timeline on the submission of financial reports and transaction documents as provided in Item 7.2.1(a) of COA Circular No. 2009-006; 
b.Direct the Municipal Accountant to immediately submit the required financial documents and reports not yet submitted for CY 2023 to the Office of the Auditor; 

c. 	In coordination with the Human Resource/Personnel and Accounting Office, evaluate/assess the Accounting Office’s current manpower and the workload of each employee and based on the results of the assessment, make and/or recommend necessary adjustments in the delegation of tasks to concerned personnel or in the Office’s composition to address the delay in submission of reports, if necessary;  

d. 	Evaluate other effective and efficient ways of securing file copies, such as by the use of electronic means, in order to fast track the segregation of the DVs;

e. 	If necessary, impose appropriate sanctions to the concerned officers and employees as provided in Sections 122, 127 and 128 of P. D. No. 1445.

